--- In junit@y..., Mike Duffy &lt;mduffy_lists@y...&gt; wrote:
&gt; I think the only requirement for JUnit is that test names begin with
&gt; &quot;test&quot; so that they can be run through intropsection.
&gt; 

That&#39;s not required (at least not enforced).  Test names can be 
whatever you like.  *If* you want to run with introspection, the test 
names must start with &quot;test&quot;.  But there are other ways to run tests, 
like overriding &quot;runTest&quot;, for instance.  Or providing a suite() 
method.  The JUnit Cookbook has this example:

public static Test suite() { 
    TestSuite suite= new TestSuite(); 
    suite.addTest(new MoneyTest(&quot;testMoneyEquals&quot;)); 
    suite.addTest(new MoneyTest(&quot;testSimpleAdd&quot;)); 
    return suite;
}

but it would work the same (though maybe not be as readable) if 
the &quot;test&quot; methods were renamed:

public static Test suite() {
    TestSuite suite= new TestSuite();
    suite.addTest(new MoneyTest(&quot;moneyEqualsCheck&quot;));
    suite.addTest(new MoneyTest(&quot;simpleAddCheck&quot;));
    return suite;
}


Someone else claimed the &quot;test&quot; prefix was a requirement recently 
(message 2126).  If I&#39;m wrong and it is a req, please correct me.
